revision.text:
'''-''abad''''' is a [[suffix]] that forms part of many west, central and south Asian [[toponymy|city names]] originally derived from the [[Persian language]] term ''{{transl|fa|[[wikt:آباد|ābād]]}}'' ({{lang|fa|آباد}}), meaning "cultivated place" (village, city, region), and commonly attached to the name of the city's founder or patron.
In India, -''abad''s are the legacies of [[Islamic rulers in the Indian subcontinent|Persianized Muslim rulers]] such as the [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]].
The suffix is most common in Iran, which contains thousands of -''abad''s, most of them small villages. [[Markazi Province]] alone contained 44 [[Hoseynabad (disambiguation)|Hoseynabad]]s, 31 [[Aliabad (disambiguation)|Aliabad]]s, 23 [[Hajjiabad (disambiguation)|Hajjiabad]]s, 22 [[Hasanabad (disambiguation)|Hasanabad]]s, and so on.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-mwASd8Js5UC&pg=PT26&dq=abad | title=Cotton, climate, and camels in early Islamic Iran: a moment in world history | publisher=[[Columbia University Press]] | author=[[Richard Bulliet]] | year=2013}}</ref>
