{{short description|An ancient microcontinent or terrane that collided with Río de la Plata Craton and Río Apas Craton during the late Proterozoic and early Cambrian}}
{{Geology of the Andes}}

'''Pampia'''<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.gsf.2011.11.004 |title=A history of Proterozoic terranes in southern South America: From Rodinia to Gondwana |journal=Geoscience Frontiers |volume=3 |issue=2 |pages=137–45 |year=2012 |last1=Casquet |first1=C |last2=Rapela |first2=C.W |last3=Pankhurst |first3=R.J |last4=Baldo |first4=E.G |last5=Galindo |first5=C |last6=Fanning |first6=C.M |last7=Dahlquist |first7=J.A |last8=Saavedra |first8=J }}</ref> was an ancient [[microcontinent]] or [[terrane]] that collided with [[Río de la Plata Craton]] and [[Rio Apa craton|Río Apas Craton]] during the [[Pampean orogeny]] of late [[Proterozoic]] and early [[Cambrian]].<ref>{{Cite book |doi=10.1016/S0166-2635(09)01609-0 |chapter=Palaeogeography |title=Neoproterozoic-Cambrian Tectonics, Global Change and Evolution: A Focus on South Western Gondwana |volume=16 |pages=131–41 |series=Developments in Precambrian Geology |year=2009 |last1=Gaucher |first1=Claudio |last2=Bossi |first2=Jorge |last3=Blanco |first3=Gonzalo |isbn=978-0-444-53249-7 }}</ref> It was one of the first terranes to be amalgamated to the old [[craton]]s of the east, and was followed by the suturing of [[Cuyania]] and [[Chilenia]] terranes into the young [[South American Plate]].

==Sources==
