{{For|the adjacent town in Switzerland|Rheinfelden}} {{Expand German|topic=geo|date=February 2009|Rheinfelden (Baden)}} {{Infobox German location |name = Rheinfelden |type = Stadt |image_photo = Josephskirche Rheinfelden.jpg |image_caption = Saint Joseph Church |image_coa = Wappen Rheinfelden Baden.png |coordinates = {{coord|47|33|40|N|7|47|30|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |image_plan = |state = Baden-Württemberg |region = Freiburg |district = Lörrach |elevation = 280 |area = 62.84 |population = 32469 |Stand = 2006-12-31 |postal_code = 79618 |PLZ-alt = 7888 |area_code = 07623 |licence = LÖ |Gemeindeschlüssel = 08 3 36 069 |divisions = 8 |Straße = Kirchplatz 2 |website = [http://www.rheinfelden-baden.de/ www.rheinfelden-baden.de] |mayor = Eberhard Niethammer |party = CDU }}
'''Rheinfelden''' ({{lang-gsw|Badisch-Rhyfälde}}, {{IPA-gsw|ˈb̥ad̥ɪʃ ʁifæld̥ə|pron}}) is a town in the [[Lörrach (district)|district of Lörrach]] in [[Baden-Württemberg]], [[Germany]]. It is situated on the right bank of the [[Rhine]], across from [[Rheinfelden]], [[Switzerland]], and 15&nbsp;km east of [[Basel]]. The population is 32,469 as of 2006, making it the second most populated town of the district after [[Lörrach]].
==Geography== Rheinfelden is located on the Swiss-German border, between the [[High Rhine]] to the south and the [[Dinkelberg]] hills to the north in the [[Lörrach (district)|district of Lörrach]]. It borders the Swiss town of the same name across the Rhine river, and the towns of [[Grenzach-Wyhlen]], [[Inzlingen]], [[Steinen, Baden-Württemberg|Steinen]], [[Maulburg]], [[Schopfheim]], [[Schwörstadt]], and [[Wehr, Baden-Württemberg|Wehr]] in Germany.
===Communities=== Rheinfelden consists of a relatively young city core (founded in the late 19th Century), two formerly independent villages ([[Nollingen]] and [[Warmbach]]), and seven villages which were incorporated into the city between 1972 and 1975. These are: *[[Degerfelden]] ([[Alemannic German|alem.]] ''Degerfälde''). *[[Minseln]] (alem. ''Meisele''). *[[Herten, Rheinfelden|Herten]] (alem. ''Herte''). *[[Nordschwaben]] (alem. ''Nordschwoobe''). *[[Adelhausen]] (alem. ''Adelhuuse''). *[[Eichsel]] (alem. ''Eiggsle'') *[[Karsau, Germany|Karsau]] (alem. ''Charsau'') and its community of Beuggen (alem. ''Büügge'').
Apart from the city core, the villages forming Rheinfelden date from the early Middle Ages. Partly because of this, a teasing animosity exists between the villages with their longer history and traditions, and the industrial city core with its diverse population of recent origin.
==Famous people== *[[Ruwen Faller]], (born 1980), gold medallist in 400m and 4x400m relay at the [[1999 European Athletics Junior Championships]] *[[Anne-Sophie Mutter]], (born 1963), violinist
